  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>If a buyer's agent contacts your listing agent to say they have a client interested in your property, and that transaction proceeds to settlement, the sale is described as a conjunctional sale. Two agents are involved: your appointed listing agent and the buyer's agent representing the purchaser. How the commission is handled, and whether you as the seller end up paying more, is something sellers in Brisbane's inner east increasingly need to understand as buyer's agency becomes a more common feature of the market.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a conjunctional sale actually is</h2>
      <p>In a conjunctional sale, the listing agent and the buyer's agent jointly facilitate the transaction. The buyer's agent has sourced or identified the buyer and is acting in that buyer's interests, while the listing agent is acting in your interests as the seller. Both agents are involved in the negotiation and both expect to be compensated.</p>

      <p>The key question for sellers is: who pays the buyer's agent? In most residential conjunctional sales in Queensland, the commission paid by the seller to the listing agent is shared between the listing agent and the buyer's agent. The total commission you pay does not automatically increase simply because a buyer's agent is involved, though the split arrangement means your listing agent receives a smaller portion of the commission than they would on a direct sale.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How commission is split</h2>
      <p>The commission split in a conjunctional sale is a matter of negotiation between the two agents. A common arrangement is a 50/50 split of the total commission, though the actual division varies depending on the agents involved, the nature of the transaction, and what is specified in your Form 6 authority.</p>

      <p>In some cases, particularly where the buyer's agent has contributed significant work in finding and preparing the buyer, the split may be weighted towards the buyer's agent. In others, where the listing agent has done the majority of the campaign work and the buyer's agent has simply introduced a client at the final stage, the listing agent may retain a larger share.</p>

      <p>What matters for you as a seller is whether the total commission you pay changes. In most cases it does not: you pay the agreed commission rate to the listing agent, and the listing agent handles the split with the buyer's agent internally. However, some listing agents will seek to charge an additional fee where a conjunctional arrangement is involved. This should be disclosed in your Form 6 and is something to raise explicitly with your agent before signing.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to check in your Form 6</h2>
      <p>Your Form 6 should specify whether the listing agent is permitted to enter conjunctional arrangements and under what conditions. Read the rebate and referral section carefully. If the Form 6 is silent on conjunctional arrangements and a buyer's agent becomes involved, your listing agent should disclose this to you and confirm the commission structure before proceeding.</p>

      <p>Queensland's property agent regulations require agents to disclose any arrangement where commission is shared with another party. If your listing agent does not disclose a conjunctional arrangement proactively, that is a compliance issue worth raising directly. In practice, most experienced agents in Brisbane's inner east handle this transparently, but it pays to understand what you have agreed to before the campaign starts rather than during negotiations.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The growing role of buyer's agents in Brisbane's inner east</h2>
      <p>Buyer's agency has grown substantially in Brisbane's inner east over the past several years. In suburbs such as Bulimba, Hawthorne, Morningside, and Norman Park, it is now common for 15 to 25 per cent of buyers at the more active price points to be working with a buyer's agent. These buyers tend to be serious, pre-qualified, and able to move quickly, which from a seller's perspective is genuinely useful.</p>

      <p>A buyer's agent introducing a well-qualified purchaser into your campaign can accelerate the sale timeline and improve the negotiating dynamic, particularly if your campaign has been running for several weeks without a strong offer. The presence of a motivated buyer who has already committed to a buyer's agent fee signals genuine purchase intent, which changes how your listing agent can position the negotiation.</p>

      <p>The tension for sellers arises when the listing agent's financial incentive may be affected by the conjunctional arrangement. A listing agent who earns half the normal commission on a conjunctional sale has less financial incentive to push hard for a higher price in the final negotiation. This does not mean they will underperform, but it is worth having an honest conversation with your agent about how they approach conjunctional negotiations and whether their interests remain aligned with yours throughout the process.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Does using a buyer's agent mean the buyer pays less?</h2>
      <p>Not necessarily. Buyer's agents are primarily paid to find properties that are right for their client and to negotiate effectively on their behalf. Their involvement does not automatically mean the buyer will offer less or push harder on price. In competitive situations, a buyer's agent may actually encourage their client to offer more quickly and firmly to secure the property before competing buyers act.</p>

      <p>What buyer's agents do tend to do well is identify properties that suit their client's brief before they are widely known, which can result in pre-campaign or off-market transactions. If your listing agent is approached by a buyer's agent before you have formally launched, it is worth considering the offer seriously if the price and terms are right, while being mindful that you may not have fully tested the market at that point.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Managing the relationship during negotiations</h2>
      <p>When a buyer's agent is involved, your listing agent should remain your sole point of contact for negotiations. All communication about price, terms, and conditions goes through the listing agent to the buyer's agent, then to the buyer. The buyer's agent is not your agent and is not acting in your interests, so direct communication with a buyer's agent during an active negotiation is not advisable without your listing agent present.</p>

      <p>Your listing agent is responsible for managing the conjunctional relationship professionally. That means keeping you informed of who the buyer's agent is, what their track record looks like, and how the negotiations are progressing. A listing agent who is uncomfortable with buyer's agents or who handles conjunctional arrangements poorly is a liability in a market where buyer's agency is increasingly common.</p>

